WEBVTT

1
00:05:00.720 --> 00:05:05.271
Bio readouts are all in the green.
Looks like she's alive.

2
00:05:07.765 --> 00:05:10.767
Well, there goes
our salvage, guys.

3
00:05:37.211 --> 00:05:40.339
- How are we today?
- Terrible.

4
00:05:40.423 --> 00:05:43.300
Well, better than
yesterday, at least.

5
00:05:43.384 --> 00:05:46.136
- Where am I?
- You're safe.

6
00:05:46.220 --> 00:05:48.638
You're at Gateway Station.
Been here a couple of days.

7
00:05:48.723 --> 00:05:52.142
You were pretty groggy at first,
but now you're okay.

8
00:05:52.226 --> 00:05:54.728
Looks like you've got a visitor.

9
00:05:56.606 --> 00:05:58.940
Jonesy. Come here.

10
00:06:00.109 --> 00:06:02.235
Hey, come here.

11
00:06:02.320 --> 00:06:04.696
How are you, you stupid cat?

12
00:06:04.781 --> 00:06:08.700
How are you? Where have you been?

13
00:06:08.785 --> 00:06:12.621
- Guess you two have met?
- I'm Burke. Carter Burke.

14
00:06:12.705 --> 00:06:17.250
I work for the company, but don't let
that fool you. I'm really an okay guy.

15
00:06:18.544 --> 00:06:20.462
I'm glad to see you're
feeling a little better.

16
00:06:20.546 --> 00:06:24.091
They tell me that all the weakness
and disorientation should pass soon.

17
00:06:24.217 --> 00:06:30.097
That's just natural side effects of such an
unusually long hypersleep, or something like that.

18
00:06:30.181 --> 00:06:32.349
What do you mean?

19
00:06:32.433 --> 00:06:34.810
How long was I out there?

20
00:06:34.894 --> 00:06:36.978
Inhalation Therapy, report to-

21
00:06:37.063 --> 00:06:39.314
Has no one discussed
this with you yet?

22
00:06:39.399 --> 00:06:41.400
No. But, I mean...

23
00:06:41.484 --> 00:06:45.487
I don't... recognize this place.

24
00:06:45.571 --> 00:06:47.572
No, I know. Uh-

25
00:06:47.657 --> 00:06:51.368
Okay. It's just that,
this might be a shock to you.

26
00:06:51.494 --> 00:06:54.079
- It's long-
- How long?

27
00:06:54.163 --> 00:06:56.164
Please.

28
00:06:57.166 --> 00:07:01.128
- 57 years.
- What?

29
00:07:01.212 --> 00:07:05.465
That's the thing.
You were out there for 57 years.

30
00:07:05.550 --> 00:07:08.677
What happened was you had drifted
right through the core systems.

31
00:07:08.761 --> 00:07:11.596
And it's really
just blind luck...

32
00:07:11.681 --> 00:07:14.891
that a deep-salvage team
found you when they did.

33
00:07:14.976 --> 00:07:17.269
It's one in a thousand, really.

34
00:07:17.353 --> 00:07:22.065
I think you're damn lucky to be alive, kiddo.
You could be floating out there forever.

35
00:07:22.150 --> 00:07:25.360
You-You okay?

36
00:07:31.784 --> 00:07:34.536
Uuh!

37
00:07:34.620 --> 00:07:36.872
You okay?

38
00:07:41.419 --> 00:07:46.214
Oh-h-h! God!

39
00:07:47.633 --> 00:07:51.178
- Nurse! Please!
- God!

40
00:07:51.304 --> 00:07:54.264
Someone get in here now!

41
00:07:54.348 --> 00:07:56.391
Now!

42
00:07:56.476 --> 00:07:58.685
- Hold!
- Please.

43
00:07:58.769 --> 00:08:00.979
Hold on!

44
00:08:01.063 --> 00:08:03.064
Kill me!

45
00:08:10.740 --> 00:08:14.659
No!

46
00:08:20.458 --> 00:08:23.585
Bad dreams again?
You want something to help you sleep?

47
00:08:23.669 --> 00:08:25.921
No.

48
00:08:26.005 --> 00:08:28.006
I've slept enough.

49
00:08:29.926 --> 00:08:32.177
Jonesy.

50
00:08:32.261 --> 00:08:34.262
Come here.

51
00:08:34.347 --> 00:08:36.431
Shh.

52
00:08:40.728 --> 00:08:42.729
It's all right.

53
00:08:43.731 --> 00:08:47.526
It's all right now.

54
00:08:47.610 --> 00:08:49.653
It's over.

55
00:08:52.740 --> 00:08:54.991
I'd just like to go, -

56
00:08:55.076 --> 00:08:57.244
back to this point about
the override destruct order.

57
00:08:57.370 --> 00:09:00.914
- Is it in the file?
- I don't understand this.

58
00:09:00.998 --> 00:09:03.500
We have been here
for three and a half hours.

59
00:09:03.584 --> 00:09:05.752
Now, how many different ways do
you want me to tell the same story?

60
00:09:07.129 --> 00:09:11.758
Look at it from our
perspective, please.

61
00:09:11.842 --> 00:09:13.843
Please?

62
00:09:16.264 --> 00:09:18.723
Now, you freely admit to
detonating the engines of,

63
00:09:18.808 --> 00:09:21.643
and thereby destroying,
an M-class starfreighter,

64
00:09:21.727 --> 00:09:24.187
a rather expensive piece
of hardware.

65
00:09:24.272 --> 00:09:27.482
Forty-two million
in adjusted dollars.

66
00:09:27.566 --> 00:09:30.318
That's minus payload, of course.

67
00:09:30.403 --> 00:09:34.781
The lifeboat's flight recorder
corroborates some elements of your account,

68
00:09:34.865 --> 00:09:39.911
in that, for reasons unknown,
the Nostromo set down on LV-426,

69
00:09:39.996 --> 00:09:44.541
an unsurveyed planet at that time,
that it resumed its course...

70
00:09:44.625 --> 00:09:49.546
and was subsequently set for
self-destruct by you for reasons unknown.

71
00:09:49.630 --> 00:09:51.965
Not for reasons unknown.
I told you.

72
00:09:52.091 --> 00:09:57.804
We set down there on company orders to
get this thing, which destroyed my crew...

73
00:09:57.888 --> 00:10:00.348
and your expensive ship.

74
00:10:00.433 --> 00:10:04.102
The analysis team, which went over
the lifeboat centimeter by centimeter,

75
00:10:04.186 --> 00:10:07.314
found no physical evidence
of the creature you describe.

76
00:10:07.398 --> 00:10:11.443
Good! That's because I blew it
out of the goddamn air lock,

77
00:10:13.112 --> 00:10:15.196
like I said.

78
00:10:16.949 --> 00:10:21.536
Are there any species like this
hostile organism on LV-426?

79
00:10:21.620 --> 00:10:24.122
No. It's a rock.
No indigenous life.

80
00:10:26.125 --> 00:10:29.711
Did I.Q.'s just drop sharply
while I was away?

81
00:10:29.795 --> 00:10:32.172
Ma'am, I already said
it was not indigenous.

82
00:10:32.256 --> 00:10:35.008
It was a derelict spacecraft.
It was an alien ship.

83
00:10:35.092 --> 00:10:39.679
It was not from there. Do you get it?
We homed in on its beacon.

84
00:10:39.764 --> 00:10:42.557
And found something
never recorded once...

85
00:10:42.641 --> 00:10:46.144
in over 300 surveyed worlds.

86
00:10:46.228 --> 00:10:50.025
"A creature that gestates
inside a living human host."

87
00:10:50.051 --> 00:10:51.049
Yes.

88
00:10:51.108 --> 00:10:55.028
These are your words.
"And has concentrated acid for blood."

89
00:10:55.112 --> 00:10:57.364
That's right.

90
00:10:57.448 --> 00:11:01.368
Look. I can see
where this is going,

91
00:11:01.452 --> 00:11:03.870
but I'm telling you
that those things exist.

92
00:11:03.996 --> 00:11:07.165
- Thank you, Officer Ripley. That will be all.
- Please. You're not listening to me.

93
00:11:07.249 --> 00:11:09.751
Kane, the crew member-

94
00:11:09.835 --> 00:11:13.546
Kane, who went into that ship,
said he saw thousands of eggs there.

95
00:11:13.672 --> 00:11:15.715
- Thousands.
- Thank you. That will be all.

96
00:11:15.800 --> 00:11:17.842
Goddamn it, that's not all!

97
00:11:17.927 --> 00:11:21.638
Because if one of those things gets down
here, then that will be all!

98
00:11:21.722 --> 00:11:24.265
Then all of this- this bullshit
that you think is so important-

99
00:11:24.350 --> 00:11:28.144
You can just kiss
all of that good-bye!

100
00:11:43.577 --> 00:11:45.662
That could have been better.

101
00:11:45.788 --> 00:11:49.249
- Look, I think the- Ripley?
- Van Leuwen.

102
00:11:49.333 --> 00:11:52.585
Why don't you
just check out LV-426?

103
00:11:52.670 --> 00:11:56.423
Because I don't have to.
There have been people there for over 20 years,

104
00:11:56.549 --> 00:11:59.382
and they never complained
about any hostile organism.

105
00:11:59.408 --> 00:12:01.244
What do you mean? What people?

106
00:12:01.303 --> 00:12:04.431
Terraformers. Planet engineers.

107
00:12:04.515 --> 00:12:08.226
They go in, set up these big atmosphere
processors to make the air breathable.

108
00:12:08.310 --> 00:12:10.603
Takes decades.

109
00:12:10.688 --> 00:12:12.939
It's what we call
a "Shake 'N Bake" colony.

110
00:12:13.023 --> 00:12:16.651
How many are there?
How many colonists?

111
00:12:16.735 --> 00:12:21.239
- I don't know-60, maybe 70 families.
- Do you mind?

112
00:12:23.909 --> 00:12:25.910
Families.

113
00:12:28.164 --> 00:12:30.165
Jesus.

114
00:13:06.785 --> 00:13:08.995
Hiya, Ripley.
This is Lieutenant Gorman...

115
00:13:09.079 --> 00:13:12.207
of the Colonial Marine Corps-

116
00:13:12.291 --> 00:13:14.542
Ripley, we have to talk.

117
00:13:14.627 --> 00:13:18.338
We've lost contact
with the colony on LV-426.

118
00:13:24.803 --> 00:13:27.013
I don't believe this.

119
00:13:27.139 --> 00:13:31.684
You guys throw me at the wolves,
and now you want me to go back out there?

120
00:13:31.769 --> 00:13:34.354
Forget it. It's not my problem.

121
00:13:34.480 --> 00:13:38.066
- Can I finish?
- No. There's no way.

122
00:13:39.485 --> 00:13:41.569
Ripley, you wouldn't be
going in with the troops.

123
00:13:41.654 --> 00:13:43.988
I can guarantee your safety.

124
00:13:44.073 --> 00:13:46.574
These Colonial Marines
are very tough hombres.

125
00:13:46.659 --> 00:13:49.536
They're packing
state-of-the-art firepower.

126
00:13:49.620 --> 00:13:50.787
There's nothing
they can't handle.

127
00:13:52.276 --> 00:13:54.569
- Lieutenant, am I right?
- That's true.

128
00:13:54.653 --> 00:13:56.821
We've been trained to deal
with situations like this.

129
00:13:56.905 --> 00:14:00.533
Then you don't need me.
I'm not a soldier.

130
00:14:00.659 --> 00:14:03.244
Yeah, but we don't know exactly
what's going on out there.

131
00:14:03.328 --> 00:14:05.913
It may just be a downed
transmitter, okay?

132
00:14:05.998 --> 00:14:10.460
But if it's not,
I would like you there as an adviser,

133
00:14:10.544 --> 00:14:12.462
and that's all.

134
00:14:12.546 --> 00:14:15.465
Look, I don't have time for this.
I've got to get going, go to work.

135
00:14:15.549 --> 00:14:18.718
Right. I heard you're
working the cargo docks.

136
00:14:18.802 --> 00:14:20.761
That's right.

137
00:14:20.888 --> 00:14:22.921
Running loaders and
forklifts, that sort of thing?

138
00:14:22.947 --> 00:14:23.623
Yeah. So?

139
00:14:23.682 --> 00:14:26.809
Nothing. I think it's great
that you're keeping busy.

140
00:14:26.894 --> 00:14:29.437
And I know it's the only
thing that you could get.

141
00:14:29.521 --> 00:14:31.355
There's nothing wrong with it.

142
00:14:34.540 --> 00:14:37.000
What would you say if I told you
I could get you reinstated...

143
00:14:37.084 --> 00:14:39.043
as a flight officer?

144
00:14:39.169 --> 00:14:42.516
The company's already agreed
to pick up your contract.

145
00:14:42.542 --> 00:14:43.656
If I go.

146
00:14:43.716 --> 00:14:46.676
Yeah, if you go.

147
00:14:46.760 --> 00:14:48.928
Come on.
That's a second chance, kiddo.

148
00:14:49.013 --> 00:14:51.764
I think, personally, for you,
it would be the best thing in the world...

149
00:14:51.849 --> 00:14:54.726
to get out there and face this
thing, get back on the horse.

150
00:14:54.810 --> 00:14:57.729
Spare me, Burke.
I've had my psych evaluation this month.

151
00:14:57.855 --> 00:15:01.941
Yeah, I know. I've read it. You wake up every
night. Your sheets are soaking with sweat-

152
00:15:02.026 --> 00:15:04.277
I said no, and I mean it!

153
00:15:07.072 --> 00:15:09.949
Now, please leave.
I am not going back.

154
00:15:10.034 --> 00:15:13.369
And I am-I would not be
any good to you if I did.

155
00:15:13.454 --> 00:15:16.539
Okay. Shh.

156
00:15:17.958 --> 00:15:21.461
Would you do me a favor?
Just think about it.

157
00:15:24.548 --> 00:15:26.591
Thanks for the coffee.

158
00:16:34.660 --> 00:16:36.577
Hello.

159
00:16:36.662 --> 00:16:39.372
Ripley.

160
00:16:39.498 --> 00:16:43.042
- You okay?
- Just tell me one thing, Burke.

161
00:16:43.127 --> 00:16:46.421
You're going out there
to destroy them, right?

162
00:16:46.505 --> 00:16:51.426
Not to study, not to bring back,
but to wipe them out.

163
00:16:51.510 --> 00:16:55.555
That's the plan.
You have my word on it.

164
00:16:58.100 --> 00:16:59.308
All right. I'm in.

165
00:17:00.727 --> 00:17:01.310
I think that-

166
00:17:09.528 --> 00:17:11.821
And you, you little shithead,

167
00:17:11.905 --> 00:17:14.740
you're staying here.

168
00:18:39.701 --> 00:18:43.538
They ain't payin' us
enough for this, man.

169
00:18:43.622 --> 00:18:45.790
Not enough to have to wake
up to your face, Drake.

170
00:18:45.874 --> 00:18:46.541
What?

171
00:18:47.960 --> 00:18:49.210
Is that a joke?

172
00:18:49.294 --> 00:18:51.379
I wish it were.

173
00:18:51.463 --> 00:18:56.384
Hey, Hicks. Man, you look
just like I feel.

174
00:18:56.468 --> 00:19:00.346
All right, sweethearts.
What are you waiting for?

175
00:19:00.430 --> 00:19:03.558
Breakfast in bed?
Another glorious day in the corps.

176
00:19:03.642 --> 00:19:07.144
A day in the Marine Corps
is like a day on the farm-

177
00:19:07.229 --> 00:19:12.191
every meal's a banquet, every paycheck a
fortune, every formation a parade.

178
00:19:12.317 --> 00:19:13.985
- I love the corps!
- Christ!

179
00:19:14.069 --> 00:19:15.903
Man, this floor is freezing!

180
00:19:16.029 --> 00:19:18.443
What do you want me to do?
Fetch your slippers for ya?

181
00:19:18.469 --> 00:19:20.224
Gee, would you, sir?
I'd like that.

182
00:19:20.284 --> 00:19:23.536
Look into my eye.
Fall in, people.

183
00:19:23.620 --> 00:19:25.871
<i>Come on. Let's go.</i>

184
00:19:25.956 --> 00:19:27.915
I hate this job.

185
00:19:28.041 --> 00:19:30.710
- Crowe, Wierzbowski. Come on. On your feet.
- We got some slack coming, right?

186
00:19:30.794 --> 00:19:33.671
You had three weeks on your back, Frost.
What do you want?

187
00:19:33.755 --> 00:19:36.132
I'm talking about breathing,
not this frozen shit.

188
00:19:36.216 --> 00:19:38.509
Yeah, Top. How 'bout it?

189
00:19:41.638 --> 00:19:45.808
All right. First assembly's
in 15, people. Shag it.

190
00:19:47.060 --> 00:19:49.687
Hey, Mira. Who's Snow White?

191
00:19:49.771 --> 00:19:53.232
She's supposed to be
some kind of consultant.

192
00:19:53.317 --> 00:19:55.568
Apparently,
she saw an alien once.

193
00:19:55.652 --> 00:19:58.696
Whoopee-fuckin'-do!
Hey, I'm impressed.

194
00:19:58.780 --> 00:20:00.823
Â¡Que bonita!

195
00:20:03.160 --> 00:20:07.288
Hey, Vasquez.
Have you ever been mistaken for a man?

196
00:20:07.372 --> 00:20:09.415
No. Have you?

197
00:20:09.499 --> 00:20:14.337
Ha, ha! Vasquez.
You're just too bad.

198
00:20:25.182 --> 00:20:27.725
Hey, Top, what's the op?

199
00:20:27.809 --> 00:20:29.935
It's a rescue mission.
You'll love it.

200
00:20:30.020 --> 00:20:34.732
There's some juicy colonists' daughters
we have to rescue from their virginity.

201
00:20:34.816 --> 00:20:36.984
Dumb-ass colonists.

202
00:20:39.571 --> 00:20:43.199
- What's this crap supposed to be?
- Vasquez.

203
00:20:43.325 --> 00:20:46.410
- Corn bread, I think.
- It's good for you, boy. Eat it.

204
00:20:46.495 --> 00:20:49.497
Hey, sure wouldn't mind getting some
more of that Arcturian poontang.

205
00:20:49.581 --> 00:20:54.710
- Remember that time?
- Yeah. Except the one that you had was male.

206
00:20:54.795 --> 00:20:57.380
Doesn't matter
when it's Arcturian.

207
00:20:57.506 --> 00:20:59.924
- Hey, Bishop, man. Do the thing with the knife.
- Please.

208
00:21:00.050 --> 00:21:02.468
Oh, come on. Yeah.

209
00:21:02.552 --> 00:21:04.512
All right! Yeah.

210
00:21:04.596 --> 00:21:08.182
- I don't want to see that, man.
- Come on, man. All right. All right.

211
00:21:08.266 --> 00:21:11.227
Hey, what are you doing, man?
What are you doing?

212
00:21:11.353 --> 00:21:13.479
- Come on. Quit messing around, Drake.
- Hudson, shut up!

213
00:21:13.563 --> 00:21:16.148
- Bishop, hey, man.
- Do it, Bishop!

214
00:21:16.233 --> 00:21:19.819
- Hey! Not me, man! Quit messing around!
- Yeah, you! Don't move.

215
00:21:19.903 --> 00:21:22.196
Trust me.

216
00:21:23.490 --> 00:21:25.408
Aah!

217
00:21:33.917 --> 00:21:36.877
All right. Knock it off,
knock it off.

218
00:21:36.962 --> 00:21:38.963
Thank you.

219
00:21:41.425 --> 00:21:43.426
- There you go, short shit.
- Enjoy your meal.

220
00:21:43.510 --> 00:21:46.262
That wasn't funny, man.

221
00:21:49.808 --> 00:21:52.935
- Lieutenant Gorman? Mr. Burke?
- Yeah, thanks.

222
00:21:53.019 --> 00:21:58.190
Looks like the new lieutenant's too
good to eat with the rest of us grunts.

223
00:21:59.609 --> 00:22:02.778
Boy's definitely got
a corncob up his ass.

224
00:22:03.864 --> 00:22:06.574
Thought you never miss, Bishop.

225
00:22:09.870 --> 00:22:12.663
You never said anything about an
android being on board. Why not?

226
00:22:12.748 --> 00:22:16.792
It never- never occurred to me.

227
00:22:16.877 --> 00:22:19.962
It's just common practice.
We always have a synthetic on board.

228
00:22:20.046 --> 00:22:22.506
I prefer the term
"artificial person" myself.

229
00:22:22.591 --> 00:22:24.467
Right.

230
00:22:24.551 --> 00:22:27.219
- Is there a problem?
- I'm sorry.

231
00:22:27.304 --> 00:22:29.221
I don't know why I didn't even-

232
00:22:29.306 --> 00:22:32.725
Ripley's last trip out,
the syn-the artificial person malfunctioned.

233
00:22:32.809 --> 00:22:34.029
Malfunctioned?

234
00:22:34.055 --> 00:22:37.713
There were problems and
a few deaths were involved.

235
00:22:37.773 --> 00:22:40.983
I'm shocked.
Was it an older model?

236
00:22:41.067 --> 00:22:43.736
The Hyperdyne Systems

237
00:22:43.820 --> 00:22:46.405
That explains it then.
The A2s always were a bit twitchy.

238
00:22:46.490 --> 00:22:49.200
That could never happen now
with our behavioral inhibitors.

239
00:22:49.284 --> 00:22:53.871
It is impossible for me to harm, or by omission
of action, allow to be harmed, a human being.

240
00:22:53.955 --> 00:22:58.167
- You sure you don't want some?

241
